  "biography_html": "<div class=\"research-section\">\n<p class=\"research-text\">Antimachus of Colophon was a Greek poet and scholar active around 400 BCE. Ancient sources describe him as a learned poet whose textual criticism of Homer influenced later Alexandrian scholars. Anecdotes highlight his erudite and difficult style, noting that he composed his elegy <strong>Lyde</strong> after the death of his beloved and that only Plato was an attentive audience for his epic <strong>Thebaid</strong>.</p>\n<p class=\"research-text\">His works survive only in fragments. The major ones are the epic <strong>Thebaid</strong>, concerning the Seven Against Thebes; the long narrative elegy <strong>Lyde</strong>, which collected tales of tragic love; <strong>Artemis</strong>, a hexameter poem; and <strong>Deltoi</strong>, a work of unknown content.</p>\n<p class=\"research-text\">Antimachus is a pivotal figure bridging Classical and Hellenistic poetry. His learned, allusive, and deliberately obscure verse sparked a famous literary debate in Alexandria, with Callimachus rejecting his style and Crates of Mallus defending it. His scholarship and poetic aesthetic established him as a key precursor to Hellenistic poetics.</p>\n</div>",
